<br>
i think you need to work on the style a bit. it looks kind of like you're trying a sort of associative writing style (first person narration lends itself to that) but i don't really feel like i'm inside your narrator's head. <br>
<br>
why does he sit at the window all day? he says he's a bard (sort of) but why doesn't he spend his days in the tavern collecting and telling tales? and (in my opinion) he needs a better explanation of why he stays in the town. maybe he was just tired of traveling and the people seemed to be pleasent. or it reminded him of the town he was born in. <br>
<br>
the trick with first person narration is that the reader really needs to be inside the character telling the story. although you don't have to reveal every detail you can't skip over things nearly as much as you can with a story told in third person. <br>
<br>
basically, if you're interested in whatever story you're telling you should always keep going. writing anything is always great practice even if you end up later scrapping the idea or starting over. <br>
<br>
anyway, just my two cents. <br>
<br>
